      <div class='inspiration'>
        <p>The Voyager 1 and Voyager 2 space probes were launched by NASA in 1977 to study the planetary systems of Jupiter and Saturn.  In 2012, the Voyager 1 craft became the first human-made object to enter interstellar space, traveling further than anyone, or anything, in history.</p>
        <p>Before NASA launched Voyager 1, Carl Sagan and a U.N. team were tasked with creating a “Golden Record” to be included in the spacecraft’s payload. The final product contains musical recordings, spoken greetings in 55 languages, and the voice of Carl Sagan’s own son saying, “Hello from the children of Planet Earth.” </p>
        <p>Relative to the vastness of space, the Golden Record is tiny, and even the team who built it acknowledge it is unlikely to be found. Rather, the intent is inspirational, not practical, as Carl Sagan noted: “The spacecraft will be encountered and the record played only if there are advanced spacefaring civilizations in interstellar space. But the launching of this bottle into the cosmic ocean says something very hopeful about life on this planet.”</p>
